## Why Asked
Understanding eventual consistency is fundamental to designing scalable distributed systems. Interviewers want to assess your knowledge of the CAP theorem trade-offs and when to choose availability over strong consistency.

## Key Concepts

- Eventual consistency guarantees that all nodes will eventually have the same data after a sufficient time without new writes
- Writes are propagated asynchronously, allowing for higher availability and partition tolerance
- Common implementations include Dynamo-style databases, Cassandra, and DNS systems
- Trade-off: reads may return stale data during the convergence window

## Code Example

```javascript
// Simplified eventual consistency model
class ReplicatedStore {
  async write(key, value) {
    const nodes = this.getNodes();

    // Write to all nodes asynchronously (no blocking)
    const writePromises = nodes.map(node => 
      node.set(key, value)
    );

    // Don't wait for all writes to complete
    return Promise.resolve('write initiated');
  }

  async read(key) {
    // May read from any node - may get stale data
    const node = this.getRandomNode();
    return node.get(key);
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How does eventual consistency differ from strong consistency?
- When would you choose eventual consistency over strong consistency?
- How do you handle read-after-write consistency in eventually consistent systems?

