## Code Example
```typescript
// Saga orchestrator with compensation
class OrderSaga {
  async execute(order: Order) {
    try {
      await this.reserveInventory(order);
      await this.processPayment(order);
      await this.executeTrade(order);
    } catch (error) {
      await this.compensate(order);
      throw error;
    }
  }

  private async compensate(order: Order) {
    await Promise.allSettled([
      this.cancelTrade(order),
      this.refundPayment(order),
      this.releaseInventory(order)
    ]);
  }
}
```

## Interview Context
This question evaluates distributed systems design skills for high-traffic applications, testing understanding of data partitioning, fault tolerance, and scalability patterns.

## Key Concepts
- **Consistent Hashing**: Maps keys to virtual nodes on a ring, minimizing remapping during scaling
- **Virtual Nodes**: Multiple hash points per physical node for better load distribution
- **Replication**: Data redundancy across nodes for fault tolerance
- **Quorum Operations**: Ensuring data consistency during reads/writes

## NFRs & Calculations
- **Throughput**: 100M DAU × 50 requests/sec = 5B requests/day
- **Latency**: <10ms for cache hits, <100ms for misses
- **Availability**: 99.99% through replica sets and automatic failover
- **Scalability**: Linear scaling with 1-2% data movement per node addition
- **Storage**: 50TB total cache (500GB per node with 100 nodes)

## Implementation Details
```javascript
// Consistent hashing ring implementation
class ConsistentHashRing {
  constructor(replicas = 160) {
    this.ring = new Map();
    this.replicas = replicas;
  }

  addNode(nodeId) {
    for (let i = 0; i < this.replicas; i++) {
      const key = `${nodeId}:${i}`;
      const hash = this.hash(key);
      this.ring.set(hash, nodeId);
    }
  }

  getNode(key) {
    const hash = this.hash(key);
    const nodes = Array.from(this.ring.keys()).sort((a, b) => a - b);
    const index = nodes.findIndex(h => h >= hash);
    return this.ring.get(nodes[index === -1 ? 0 : index]);
  }
}
```

## Real-World Examples
- **DynamoDB**: Uses consistent hashing with virtual nodes for partitioning
- **Cassandra**: Implements token ring distribution with vnodes
- **Redis Cluster**: Employs hash slots for data distribution

